column2: What is your level of proficiency in English?
column3:
"Joe designed his shoes to look like dollar bills, so he can foot the bill all day."
Does Joe pay the bills all day?
column4:
"Before Alice made the grade standard at the school, every teacher used a different notation."
Did Alice pass an exam or create a scoring system?
column5:
"King Julian directed all the rage towards poor Mort."
Is the statement describing an emotion or a trend?
column6:
"The two soldiers crossed the narrow and shaky bridge hand in hand."
Do the two soldiers need to always be together?
column7:
"These cheap cat trees are rough and tumble easily."
Is the cat fighting?
column8:
"The model rocket got off the ground and rose into the sky."
Is the sentence describing an object’s movement or progress?
column9:
"Jack booked a room with a view of the Eiffel Tower for their vacation."
Does Jack want to see or acquire the Eiffel Tower?
column10:
"Jane decided to go without saying anything to Jack."
Is this statement about Jane saying something obvious or leaving?
column11:
"Jane gave Jack the slip containing her goodbye."
Is Jane giving Jack a piece of paper or trying to escape from him?
column12:
"The aliens tuned in on the same wavelength and accidentally heard Earth’s morning news."
Are the aliens receiving a radio frequency or sharing similar opinions?
column13:
"The android was built with a heart of gold because of the metal’s strong physical properties."
Is the heart valued for its durability or for its kindness?
column14:
"She tried to steer clear of the crowded hallway between classes."
Is she keeping her distance from the hallway, or navigating through it?
column15:
"New interns are expected to toe the line during their first few weeks."
Are new interns expected to stand in a neat line or obey the management?
column16:
"All things being equal, the team with more experience should win the match."
Is it talking about a fair scenario or identical teams?
column17:
"The cut and thrust of the debate kept the audience on the edge of their seats."
Is the sentence describing a lively argument, or an sword fight?
